Reference Module in Life SciencesBrenner's Encyclopedia of Genetics (Second Edition)2013, Pages 332–333Edited By Stanley Maloy and Kelly Hughes







Gilbert, WalterW.C. SummersAuthor Vitae Yale University, New Haven, CT, USACurrent as of  31 October 201631 October 2016Available online 1 May 20131 May 2013Reviewed  31 October 2016AbstractWalter Gilbert (1932–) is an American molecular biologist, known for his multiple contributions to genetics, including the role of messenger RNA and ribosomes in protein synthesis, mechanisms of gene expression, the first successful method for DNA sequence analysis, and conceptual advances in establishing genomics as a new science. He has also been a major proponent of the applications of molecular genetics to drug development and the biotechnology industry. Most of his career has been spent at Harvard, but he held key positions in biotechnology enterprises, including Biogen, Myriad Genetics, and the Genome Corporation. Among his many honors, Gilbert received a Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1980, sharing it with Frederick Sanger and Paul Berg.KeywordsBerg, Paul; Biotechnology; DNA sequencing; Genomics; Gilbert, Walter; Lactose operon; Maxam–Gilbert method; mRNA; Nobel Prize; Repressor; Ribosome; Rolling circle; Sanger, FrederickVitaeWilliam C. Summers received his academic degrees (BS, MS, PhD, and MD) from the University of Wisconsin (Madison) and was an NSF postdoctoral fellow at MIT before joining the Yale faculty in 1968. At Yale, where he is a professor in several departments or programs, ranging from molecular biophysics and biochemistry to history of science and medicine, his interests have included molecular biology and genetics of cancer and viruses, history of medicine and science, and the relations between science and the humanities. He has taught and published on topics ranging from quantum mechanics, to viral genetics to the biology of gender and sexuality as well as East Asian studies.Copyright © 2013 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.












